      <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>Recall the time that Filip traveled with his kids to <xref ref="example-kicking-it-on-mars" text="custom">kick a soccer ball on Mars</xref>? We should examine one more angle to our soccer kick question. The formula <m>H(t)=-6.07t^2+27.1t</m> finds the height of the soccer ball in feet above the ground at a time <m>t</m> seconds after being kicked.
                <ol>
                    <li><p>Using technology, find out what the maximum height of the ball was and when it reached that height.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Using technology, solve for when <m>H(t)=20</m> and interpret the meaning of this in a complete sentence.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Using technology, solve for when <m>H(t)=0</m> and interpret the meaning of this in a complete sentence.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                <p>Since each of these questions revolves around using technology to find the answers, we should begin this question by making a graph of the scenario. First, keep in mind that the height cannot be a negative number in this example, so any part of the curve below the <m>t</m>-axis has been omitted.</p>
                <figure>
                    <caption>A Soccer Kick on Mars Part II</caption>
                    <image width="47%">
                        <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[axis x line=middle,
                                            axis y line=middle,
                                            xmin=-1,
                                            xmax=6,
                                            ymin=-5,
                                            ymax=35,
                                            grid=both,
                                            xtick={1,2,...,5},
                                            ytick={5,10,...,30},
                                            minor xtick=,
                                            minor ytick=,
                                            xlabel={$t$}]
                                    \addplot[domain=0:4.465, mark=*, samples=15, smooth, color=firstcolor]  {-6.07*x^2+27.1*x} node[pos=0.55, above right] {$y=H(t)$};
                                \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                            <p>To find the maximum height of the ball, we need to find the highest point on the graph. Using technology, that point is about <m>(2.23,30.25)</m>. So, the maximum occurred about <quantity><mag>2.23</mag><unit base="second" /></quantity> after being kicked and it reached a maximum height of <quantity><mag>30.25</mag><unit base="foot" /></quantity> above the ground.</p>
                            <figure>
                                <caption>A Soccer Kick on Mars Part II Maximum</caption>
                                <image width="47%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                            \begin{axis}[
                                            xmin=-1,
                                            xmax=6,
                                            ymin=-5,
                                            ymax=35,
                                            grid=both,
                                            xtick={1,2,...,5},
                                            ytick={5,10,...,30},
                                            minor xtick=,
                                            minor ytick=,
                                            xlabel={$t$}]
                                                \addplot[domain=0:4.465, color=firstcolor]  {-6.07*x^2+27.1*x} node[pos=0.65, above right] {$y=H(t)$};
                                                \addplot[soliddot, color=fifthcolor] coordinates{(2.23,30.25)} node[above right] {$(2.23,30.25)$};
                                            \end{axis}
                                        \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </sidebyside>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                            <p>To solve for when <m>H(t)=20</m>, we need to look for any points on the graph where the <m>y</m>-value is <m>20</m>. Using technology to graph the function, we can see that the the curve has a <m>y</m>-value of <m>20</m> when <m>t\approx 0.93</m> and <m>t\approx 3.53</m>. This means that at both <quantity><mag>0.93</mag><unit base="second" /></quantity> and <quantity><mag>3.53</mag><unit base="second" /></quantity> after being kicked and the soccer ball was at a height of <quantity><mag>20</mag><unit base="foot" /></quantity>.</p>
                            <figure>
                                <caption>A Soccer Kick on Mars Part II at <quantity><mag>20</mag><unit base="foot" /></quantity></caption>
                                <image width="47%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                            \begin{axis}[
                                            xmin=-1,
                                            xmax=6,
                                            ymin=-5,
                                            ymax=35,
                                            grid=both,
                                            xtick={1,2,...,5},
                                            ytick={5,10,15,25,30},
                                            minor xtick=,
                                            minor ytick=,
                                            xlabel={$t$}]
                                                \addplot[domain=0:4.465, color=firstcolor]  {-6.07*x^2+27.1*x} node[pos=0.55, above right] {$y=H(t)$};
                                                \addplot[secondcurve, domain=-1:6]  {20} node[pos=0.9, below] {$y=20$};
                                                \addplot[soliddot, color=fifthcolor] coordinates{(0.933,20)} node[below right] {$(0.93,20)$};
                                                \addplot[soliddot, color=fifthcolor] coordinates{(3.532,20)} node[above right] {$(3.35,20)$};
                                            \end{axis}
                                        \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </sidebyside>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                            <p>To solve for when <m>H(t)=0</m>, we need to look for any points on the graph where the <m>y</m>-value is <m>0</m>. Using technology to graph the function, we can see that the the curve has a <m>y</m>-value of <m>0</m> when <m>t=0</m> and <m>t\approx 4.47</m>. This means that at both <quantity><mag>0</mag><unit base="second" /></quantity> and <quantity><mag>4.47</mag><unit base="second" /></quantity> after being kicked and the soccer ball was at a height of <quantity><mag>0</mag><unit base="foot" /></quantity>. More importantly, these two times are indicating the times that the ball is on the ground just before being kicked and just as it lands.</p>
                            <figure>
                                <caption>A Soccer Kick on Mars Part II on the Ground</caption>
                                <image width="47%">
                                    <latex-image>
                                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                            \begin{axis}[
                                            xmin=-1,
                                            xmax=6,
                                            ymin=-5,
                                            ymax=35,
                                            grid=both,
                                            xtick={1,2,...,5},
                                            ytick={5,10,...,30},
                                            minor xtick=,
                                            minor ytick={20},
                                            xlabel={$t$}]
                                                \addplot[domain=0:4.465, color=firstcolor]  {-6.07*x^2+27.1*x} node[pos=0.55, above right] {$y=H(t)$};
                                                \addplot[soliddot, color=fifthcolor] coordinates{(0,0)} node[above right] {$(0,0)$};
                                                \addplot[soliddot, color=fifthcolor] coordinates{(4.465,0)} node[above left] {$(4.47,0)$};
                                            \end{axis}
                                        \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </sidebyside>
                    </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
          </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercisegroup cols="3">
        <title>Linear Equations with Fractions</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Solve the given equation. Practice clearing the denominator(s) as a first step.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise label="linear-equation-fractions-b">
          <webwork xml:id="webwork-linear-equation-fractions-b">
            <pg-code>
              Context("Fraction");
              ($m,$c) = random_subset(2,2..12);
              $b = Fraction(random_coprime([1..12],[2..12]));
              $left = Formula("$m x + $b");
              $right = Formula("$c");
              $sol = ($c - $b)/$m;
              Context("FiniteSolutionSets");
              $solution = Formula("{$sol}");
              $lcd = ($b->value)[1];
            </pg-code>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m><var name="$left"/> = <var name="$right"/></m>
              </p>
              <instruction>
                What LCD will you use?
              </instruction>
              <p>
                <var name="$lcd" width="4"/>
              </p>
              <instruction>
                Solve the equation.
              </instruction>
              <p>
                <var name="$solution" width="16"/>
              </p>
            </statement>
          </webwork>
        </exercise>
        <exercise label="linear-equation-fractions-b-copy">
          <webwork copy="webwork-linear-equation-fractions-b"/>
        </exercise>
